column168: During a routine yard check at the intermediate truck transfer facility, an 85 gallon salvage drum was found to be leaking.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and cleaned up the spilled material from the dock floor using suitable absorbents, which were then placed into the salvage drum.  The drum was leaking through the threaded closure of the lid, which had not been properly closed.  After tightening the drum per the applicable drum closure instructions, the shipment was loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The shipment consisted of 6 drums which had been exposed to the weather.  The drums were all overpacked at the time of pickup as it was decided they would not withstand the rigors of transportation.  A threaded lid overpack drum was not closed properly and began leaking after unloading at the intermediate truck transfer facility while sitting on the dock inside the building.  The driver will be counseled and retrained on proper container closure procedures

column168: A Great Lakes Petroleum tankwagon was dispatched to fill a 10,000 gallon diesel above ground storage tank (AST) owned by a construction company on November 1, 2013. The site is located at 264 Wilson Park Rd. in Statesville, NC. The customer's AST did not have an overfill prevention valve and the fuel delivery amount was overestimated. As a result, an overfill of the diesel fuel tank occurred during transport delivery.    The estimated overfill amount was approximately 100 gallons of diesel fuel. The fuel truck driver used a spill kit to stop the fuel spill and called dispatch to report the incident. Great Lakes Petroleum called their Hazmat Responder for the area. CERT (Carolina Emergency Response Team) responded to the incident that day and began clean up of the site. The spill did not reach waters/drains and was contained on gravel/dirt. CERT removed the contaminate and conducted on site field tests to confirm that all the fuel had been removed.     A report was filed with the North Carolina Department of Natural Resources (NCDENR) as the spill was greater than 25 gallons. CERT has disposed of the hazardous material per state and federal laws and an abatement report will be submitted once final lab results are conducted. It is anticipated that NCDENR will issue a NFA (No Further Action) response.    The fuel driver has been reprimanded and additional training will be conducted at Great Lakes Petroleum to ensure future risk of spills is reduced/eliminated. In addition, the company is investigating policies that will require customers who have their own fuel tanks be required to install overfill prevention valves on their tanks. The valves are designed to physically shut off during fuel delivery once the AST reaches capacity.
column169: Great Lakes Petroleum is increasing their driver training and evaluating operating procedures for fuel delivery including quarterly safety meetings and staff tests/exams. A wireless monitoring system has recently been installed that will help dispatchers correctly gauge fuel delivery amounts. Additional steps being investigated to prevent overfill include installation of overfill prevention valves on storage tanks.

column168: Tank car CTCX 725285 in the railyard was reported with fresh commodity staining on its side shell that emanated from its manway area. CTCX 725285 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting contract responders' inspection. No commodity was observed releasing from the manway closure when CTCX 725285 remained motionless and no ground impact from spillage was reported. On 11/04/2013 responders inspecting CTCX 725285 reported finding 3 of 6 manway securement bolts less than tool tight and no manway gasket applied. Responders installed a new 20 inch EPDM nozzle gasket and secured the manway closure by properly tool tightening all manway securement bolts. Spillage on CTCX 725285's side shell was cleaned. Intact shipper seal HOLLY UT 066933 at the manway closure was replaced by seal TIS 5849. Response was concluded by 1140 hrs. MST, 11/04/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While loading a plastic tote onto a trailer, the tote was accidentally punctured by a broken pallet.  As a result, approximately 80 gallons of free product were released and contained inside of the trailer. The leaking tote was flipped over to prevent additional leakage.  Wilson Trucking Corporation utilized absorbent material to contain and recover the free liquid.  Wilson Trucking Corporation will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as  a result of the cleanup.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Freight was damaged and discovered in unloading process.  Cleaned up in house.

A van trailer containing drums of hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  While doing his post trip inspection, the driver noticed a leak and residue on the side of the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer, which was parked in the concrete containment area.  The material had leaked onto the floor of the trailer due to a drum that was badly corroded on the bottom and leaked.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum and also the absorbent materials used to clean up the spill were loaded into the drum.  After unloading the trailer, it was placed out of service for cleaning.
column169: The shipment showed no signs of leaking at the time of pickup.  As the corroded area was on the bottom of the drum, it was not noticed by the driver.  The trailer had moved from PA to NC without showing any signs of leaking.  The shipper was notified of the incident and advised to inspect drums closely prior to loading them for transportation.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shippers location to Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in Bristol, CT for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. During a routine load inspection the driver discovered that approximately 8 ounces of material escaped from the upper body of the container onto the vans floor, no material hit the ground. The driver placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: A van containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was brought to the intermediate truck transfer facility the day of pickup.  While doing a routine post trip inspection, the driver noticed the floor of the trailer was wet.  He pulled the trailer into the containment area and called his supervisor.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A supersack containing the solid sludge material was leaking liquids onto the trailer floor.  The sack was loaded into a suitable salvage container and the absorbents used to clean up the material were placed into drums.  The Tennessee Emergency Managment Authority was located and assigned incident number 1873 to the case.  The cleanup was completed just before 1AM and the shipment was loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The shipper was notified that the material had too much moisture in it which caused the leak.  They will need to review their solification procedures and the drivers will be notified to insure the material is totally dried out prior to acceptance of further shipments of this material.

column168: During a routine inspection FRA Inspector Danny McCourt found tank car RAIX 6388, load of Environmentally Hazardous Substance (Ethylene Glycol), leaking from the bread box area, with product running down the sides of the car.  Dow Chemical (consignee) requested Union Tank to respond and NS requested environmental contractor Quick Response respond as well.  Investigation revealed leak to be coming from the liquid line where the valve threads on to the liquid line nipple.  Union Tank applied a 36" wrench and got about 1/4 turn on the valve which stopped the leak.  Union Tank and Quick Response cleaned the car, ties, and ballast.  Car was moved about 1/4 mile and placed into the plant that evening.  UTLX will perform a bubble leak test on the valve and nipple prior to the car being released.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While unloading a trailer, the side of the 55 gallon drum was gouged by a forklift, which resulted in a puncture.  The puncture resulted in the release of approximately 15 gallons of UN2924 material on to the trailer floor.  No material left the trailer.  An environmental contractor (National Response Corporation) was dispatched to clean up the released material.  The contractors applied absorbents to the interior of the trailer, absorbing all of the released material.  The damaged drum was then placed in an overpack drum.  The absorbent material was then containerized in a drum.  The drum withthe containerized absorbents and the overpack were then taken for disposal.

column168: Aircraft 708, departed DWC at 2050. Passing about 10,000ft the loadmaster said he smelled a chlorine-like odor. He checked the  main deck in an attempt to discover the source and encountered very strong fumes. He advised the crew, and we all went on oxygen. An emergency was declared and we returned to DWC. We were able to jettison about 40,000lbs prior to landing. After landing we were met by emergency equipment. We cleared the runway and opened the doors and hatches we had access to until the stairs arrived. We then opened up the main cargo door with the assistance of emergency crews (on oxygen) to allow the fumes to dissipate. The exact source of the fumes was not immediately identified but there were class 5.1 hazmat containers on board.  We believe that there was insufficient ullage in the containers.  4 containers appeared to have leaked. A very small quantity of material leaked.   40,000 lbs of fuel = 5891 gallons.  Current price is $2.96/gallon at Dubai = $118,000.

column168: Anhydrous Ammonia was being applied as a nutrient for crops in a farmers field on November 15, 2013. The equipment used for application was a tractor, an application chisel bar, and the wagon carrying the anhydrous ammonia storage tanks.   The running gear of the wagon had a structural failure which cause the wagon running gear to separate. The break away coupling device on the chisel applicator failed to operate properly during the separation of the running gear. Due to the failure on the break away coupling device, the hose that connected the tanks to the chisel applicator stretched and torn, which caused a release of anhydrous ammonia.   Due to the location of the release, the contents of the tanks were allowed to release to the atmosphere. The general public was not in harms way, although 2 nearby residents were asked to leave their residence as a precautionary measure in the event the wind were to change direction.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into other trailers destined for various disposal facilities.  A drum was noticed to be leaking from a pinhole leak in the side.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  10 of the 13 drums were found to have signs of deterioration and were overpacked into suitable salvage containers.  The material that had leaked onto the trailer floor was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound and also placed into a salvage drum.  The Tennessee Emergency Management Authority was notified and assigned incident number 1937.
column169: The shipper was notified of the incident and advised to use better care when choosing old drums to load for transportation.  The driver was disciplined for using poor judgement in picking up these containers for transport and also was retrained in proper container acceptance procedures.

The cause of the puncture to the bladder located within the tote was undetermined. No drains or waterways had been impacted by the release. The material was transferred into a new tote and staged onsite. The damaged tote was wrapped with pads and shrink wrap to ensure that no residual would release from it. The damaged tote was then staged onsite to be sent back to the shipper.Absorbents were worked in thoroughly to the impacted areas and containerized. column168: No package failure.  On 11/22/13 unit o7135 and trailer 631 was traveling on FM230, about 6 miles south of Weldon,Tx. The driver approached a curve in road and slowed down to about 31 mph. He began to round curve and felt a surge from trailer. As the surge progressed the trailer began to lean forcing the truck and trailer to opposite side of the roadway. The trailer fell to the soft earth on the side of the road, forcing the truck to roll onto the drivers side. The truck and trailer slid approximately 150 feet. The driver was not hurt and climbed out of the truck. He immediately checked for leaks or spillage. None was found. Driver then began notifying proper personnel to include 911. Texas State Police arrived at scene and began recovery of vehicle. No release of product was found.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that less than 1 pint of material had  escaped from the top the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris was collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container  before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been  advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, VEHICLE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN A ROLLOVER, CAUSING RELEASE. CARGO CONSISTED OF SEVENTEEN (17) 260-GALLON TOTES, WHICH CONTAINED TETRAMETHYLAMMONIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO ASPHALT ROADWAY AND ADJACENT ROADSIDE SOILS. OREGON STATE POLICE AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. BOTH LANES OF INTERSTATE 84 EAST AND WESTBOUND, WERE SHUT DOWN AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. STEVE RITCH ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSIST IN CLEANUP EFFORTS. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CLEAN AFFECTED ROADWAY AND MINIMIZE IMPACT. BOTH LANES OF I-84WERE REOPENED BY 14:00 EST, AND STEVE RITCH ENVIRONMENTAL PROCEEDED TO ASSESS THE DAMAGED TRAILER. SEVEN (7) TOTES WERE NOT BREACHED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2,600 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUID WERE RELEASED. STEVE RITCH ENVIRONMENTAL OFFLOADED THE DAMAGED TRAILER, WHICH WAS REMOVED OFF SITE FOR DISPOSITION, PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIAL INTO DAMAGED TOTES TO SOLIDIFY RESIDUALS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL, AND COORDINATED EXCAVATION OF IMPACTED SOILS. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: LeSaint Chemical Logistics will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: At approximately 0600 on 11/21/2013 the morning warehouse shift noticed liquid dripping from the bottom of a van trailer in dock#2. When opening the trailer door it was found that a 330 gallon metal systanks of hazards waste had developed a small leak about halfway down or the middle of the tank with a small stream of liquid waste running out.The cause of the leak is believed to be from a small hole developed from corrosion. Absorbent pads were placed on the ground under the trailer to prevent spreading of the material and due to the angle of the ground on which the trailer was sitting all the liquid was at the front of the trailer and no liquid ran into the warehouse. EQ Environmental was on site at the time conducting work unrelated to the spill so response time was instant. The spill was contained and cleanup completed within two hours of the spill being found..
column169: We are currently waiting for response from the tank owner Systech to provide any corrective actions on their end. Univar drivers do inspections on all drums , IBC and any other containers we pickup but have informed drivers to increase their awareness and time spent on inspections to look for small areas of concern that may not be as visible in some cases.

The driver was using a pump to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  After the unload he cleared the line the best he could by walking the hose several times.  When he went to disconnect the transfer hose from the trailer, more product was in the hose than he expected.  It knocked the bucket he was using, out of his hand, spilling the contents.  less than 2 gallons went on the asphalt.  Driver immediately put spill pads around it to keep it from spreading and the customer cleaned it up with speedy dry.
column169: The driver has since received performance enhancement training to review how to successfully clear the line after a pump unload.

The cause of the derailment remains under investigation. Subsequent to the derailment, fire and explosions occurred which resulted in damage to identification marking and placarding on all tankcars. AGR is providing the information available at this time which includes an aerial photograph of the derailment site and a summary report. Since the derailment occurred, AGR has provided employees and contract resources to extinguish all fires, transfer and store all flammable liquids (crude oil) and mitigate environmental damage caused during the derailment. The summary report attached was provided daily to resource trustees associated with response to the derailment as directed by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. A supplemental report will be provided that provides additional information related to damage and identification of tankcars when the investigation concludes.
column169: The cause for the derailment and subsequent fire and release of crude oil is presently under investigation; however, AGR performs inspections frequently, provides training regularly, makes notifications quickly, and undertakes  response actions appropriately throughout its system in order to minimize the likelihood for similar incidents to occur.

column168: A trucking terminal experienced the release of UN2054 product to the trailer floor and asphalt below from a steel tote due to a loose valve on the tote. Absorbents have been applied to the impacted asphalt and trailer floor and worked in thoroughly. All contaminated material was containerized.

A Great Lakes Petroleum driver overfilled an above ground storage tank with diesel fuel at Unified Manufacturing located at 601 East Main Street in Yadkinville, North Carolina on Nov. 25, 2013. The double walled tank was on concrete/soil and approximately 100 gallons of fuel was spilled. The spill was a result of driver error and the individual was terminated due to violations of company policy and fueling procedures. The spill did not reach any waterways or drains.    The spill was reported to the North Carolina Dept Natural Resources and the spill was cleaned up and remediated by Carolina Emergency Response Team and Lighthouse Environmental. Field testing indicates that the fuel has been completly removed from the site/soil and a technical assesment is pending. It is anticipated that a Notice of No Further Action (NFA)will be issued by the state.
column169: Great Lakes Petroleum continues to focus on driver training and we are evaluating fuel delivery procedures to prevent and reduce spills. Additional steps being investigated include the install of overfill prevenetion valves on all storage tanks. In adition, we are increasing driver penalties for driver error that result in spills. The driver from this inncident has been terminated.

column168: The truck tractor - flat bed trailer combination vehicle carrying the 8 totes of OBM MUL II was transporting thematerial from Victoria, Texas to Dilley, Texas on Highway 85 at 1:00pm on November 6, 2013. The truck rolled overcausing the material in the 275 gallon totes to be spilled when the totes were crushed. NOV's CorporateEnvironmental Risk Department was immediately notified and dispatched crews for removal of lost material, removalof truck, and remediation of impacted soil. A vacuum truck (Vac Truck Lines) arrived to the site approximately anhour after the incident and removed the remaining material in the crushed totes and the standing liquid in the ditch.The impacted soil was then removed and placed into roll-off bins for proper disposal.
column169: Additional training to truck drivers could potentially prevent future incidents from occurring.

column168: On November 9, 2013, driver Gary Smith was driving tankwagon 2071 on State Route 39 West, approximately 2 miles west of Salineville, OH. The tankwagon rolled over in a left hand curve.    Contributing factors of the rollover:     Curvy rural road  The turn in which the accident occurred sloped towards the outside of the curve  The tankwagon was partially loaded (1750 gallons in a 4500 gallon capacity)  It was dark and the driver was unfamiliar with road.  Driver was traveling too fast for road conditions.
column169: Rollover Prevention training to be accomplished as part of a Safety Standown.    Review of training program and experience of drivers for certain types of equipment and road conditions.

column168: A 55-gallon drum experienced the release of UN3082 product to the trailer floor and asphalt below due to a load shift. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site. Absorbents were applied to the impacted trailer floor and asphalt and worked in thoroughly. The damaged container was placed into an over pack drum. All contaminated material was containerized for transportation and disposal.

Trailer 67017 was almost loaded at shipper when the driver noticed a small drip under the landing gear. column168: At approximately 10:10 PM on Friday November 8, 2013 an odor of "markers" was detected by KCS personnel in the Laredo Yard in Laredo, TX. Appropriate notifications were made and emergency responders activated.     There were two cars in question initially, tank car UTLX 67117 (a loaded Cresylic Acid car) + tank car UTLX 901486 (a loaded Butyl Acrylates car). Once local responders arrived on site, the two tank cars were isolated and properly secured. Responders donned appropriate personal protective equipment (PPE), utilized air monitoring devices to check atmosphere, and accessed tank car UTLX 901486 car. After several air monitoring phases, rail car appurtenance securement check, and odor verification, tank car UTLX 901486 was cleared not to be actively leaking and responders moved on to tank car UTLX 67117.    On the UTLX 67117, it was noted that the bottom outlet valve to tank shell bolt/flanged connection was leaking (one drip per minute). It was noted that two of eight bottom outlet valve (BOV) flange bolts were less than tool tight, once tightened the leak stopped. The tank car was then isolated in the yard for more observation and air monitoring verification that the leak had stopped.     Due to the hazards associated with the commodity being shipped and the nature of the incident, it was decided that the situation had too many un-known/potentially dangerous variable and therefore the tank car would need to be transferred into a new tank car package and then home shopped for root cause investigation and repair as applicable. The field response could not verify the integrity of the seal or the condition of the sealing surface or hardware.     * There were 3 KCS employees who complained of eye irritation and therefore taken to the hospital as a precaution. They were seen and released. The symptoms improved over a short amount of time.    File Note: Item 13-the consignee information was supplied as noted from the waybill in the "consignee" section. However, the final destination for this tank car is as shown below:  Bulkamatic De Mexico S DE RL DE CV  Carreterra A Colombia KM 27 3  Full tell 011 52 818 000 2180  Salinas Victoria, Nuevo Leon 65500    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released the offeror and consignee must dialog to calculate exact about released from the amount shipped vs received at destination.    File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.    Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: An odor was reported in the railyard near two specific yard tracks. Local F.D. called to assist in finding the odor source. Tank car GATX 35960 was identified as emanating commodity vapor from its 280.5 psi pressure relief valve (PRV). GATX 35960 was cordoned-off in the railyard and main track train traffic was suspended for approximately 3 1/2 hours. A Midland PRV capping kit was successfully applied by BNSF responders which ended GATX 35960's vapor release to the atmosphere by 0048 hrs. MST, 11/18/2013. Verbal movement approval FRA-13118R5V was granted to transport GATX 35960 to the nearby consignee for unloading, which was accomplished by 1735 hrs. MST, 11/18/2013 without incident.  Visual inspection of GATX 35960's PRV revealed a small hard foreign object wedged at the valve seat possibly hampering full valve closure. However, a broken valve spring, bent or broken valve stem could not be verified, therefore these failure causes cannot be ruled out at this time.

column168: An odor of natural gas was reported in the Herington Yard near PPRX 28516.  Inspection of the car initially found no issues and no apparent source of an odor.  Further investigation found that there were elevated readings of hydrogen sulfide near the hinge side of the manway cover.  Upon opening the manway, the barrel gasket in the manway nozzle was found to be deformed and in poor condition.  Further, a second gasket was present in the groove in the manway cover as well.  Both gaskets were removed and replaced by a one-time-use gasket formed from Gore-Tex gasket material.  The car was secured and the outside rinsed with bleach to remove the odor.  Finally, in conversations with the shipper, it was determined that the odor was a mercaptan odor rather than actual hydrogen sulfide.

column168: Intermodal container SNLU 138954 after being deramped from its inbound intermodal flatcar at the intermodal facility was reported leaking a dark, oily substance. SNLU 138954 was carefully taken to the facility's containment area for lading inspection and spill remediation. Contract responders reported finding one 55 gallon steel drum (UN Spec 6HA1/X1.8/350/13/USA/M-4599) with a small corrosion hole at its bottom head which resulted from this drum's interior plastic liner failure. This leaking drum was placed into an over-pack drum. All lading, including the over-pack drum, was transferred into another suitable intermodal container for further highway transportation on 11/29/2013. This lading transfer allowed contractors to properly clean and wash all commodity spillage from SNLU 138954. Cleaning rinsate and other cleaning materials were placed into disposal drums for off-property appropriate disposal.

column168: On November 23, 2013, a 55-gallon drum on board an R&L Carriers trailer was punctured resulting in the release of approximately 25 gallons of product to the trailer floor and the roadway below. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup activities.

On 11/10/13 Transport driver was traveling on FM230 near Trinity, TX hauling 7000 gallons of diesel fuel.  As the driver entered a sharp curve at a speed of approximately 30 mph, the driver stabbed the brakes to slow down.  This caused the load to surge and the driver to lose control of the vehicle.  The transport truck rolled over onto the side of the road and come to rest.  As a result of the roll-over, one of the compartment dome covers was compromised and leaked 540 gallons of diesel fuel.  Emergency Services and Company personnel responded to the scene along with an Environmental Respone contractor.  The remaining product was transferred to another transport and the over-turned transport was then uprighted and removed from the scene.  The Environmental Response Contractor then removed the contaminated soil and returned the site to pre-accident conditions.
column169: The company will continue to train, coach, and counsel our drivers on the dangers of speeding too fast for conditions, appropriate response to roll-over potential, journey management, etc.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #34625  ON NOVEMBER 27TH, 2013, MR. DAVID HOPPER WITH ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS CONTACTED BY MS. MARY BERG OF CONWAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. (CTI). MS. BERG INFORMED MR. HOPPER THAT A CTI TRUCK HAD A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY EIGHT (8) OUNCES OF COPPER SULFATE INSIDE THE TRAILER, DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURING THE BAG WHILE OFF-LOADING THE SHIPMENT. MS. BERG REQUESTED THAT A RESPONSE BE INITIATED. UPON ARRIVAL OF RESPONSE PERSONNEL, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT APPROXIMATELY EIGHT (8) OUNCES OF COPPER SULFATE HAD BEEN RELEASED INSIDE THE VAN TRAILER, DUE TO THE FORKLIFT INCIDENT. RESPONSE PERSONNEL SWEPT UP THE COPPER SULFATE, PLACED IN A FIVE (5) GALLON PAIL, AND TRANSPORTED THE PRODUCT TO THEIR FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE. THE PUNCTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 4 INCHES WIDE ON THE BAG OF COPPER SULFATE.
column169: Although the incident was an accident, the forklift operator would benefit from additional training to insure that the incident does nothappen again.

column168: On November 26th, 2013 at 23:03 hours, Q352-26 was doubling out of the Willard East Yard, Willard, Ohio. Cars 76 to 79 derailed on the yard lead to the old main track, the resulting derailment caused the 78th car, PROX 24047, a loaded, UN 2055, Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, to release product, the cause of the release was identified as the bottom outlet valve assembly it had sustained damage during the derailment. An FRA  HazMat Investigation is in process as of the filing of this DOT 5800.1 report, Anthony Schneider is the lead FRA Inspector.  The Willard TERP was enacted, the area was isolated, the Willard Fire and Police Departments responded, local homes were evacuated for 1/2 mile, CHEMTREC was notified, report 2013-11-26-00275, product owner, BASF Chemical was notified, David White representative, Cell 973-262-7591, verified product was shipped from Styrolution Canada, LTD, from Sarnia, Ontario, Canada.  Emergency Response Contractor, EQ, Tom Wildman, cell 419-346-0795, responded, advised that at 03:33 hours, the release of product from PROX 24047 was stopped.  Local residents starting returning to their homes on November 28th, and the re-entry was completed on December 1st, 2013.  Emergency response operations continue through December 17th, 2013, to contain and recover the styrene monomer product released to the environment.    5x(5+1+0)x(5+4) = 270  Cause Code = 551 (5 points)

column168: UPS EMPLOYEES IN THE NEW STANTON HUB NOTICED A FIRE INVOLVING PACKAGES TRANSITIONING FROM A SLIDE TO A CONVEYOR BELT AT 00:21 HRS. THE FIRE ALARM WAS ACTIVIATED AND THE EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED FROM THE FACILITY. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, ARRIVING AT 00:35 HRS. THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED AND EMPLOYEES WERE CLEARED TO RETURN TO THE FACILITY AT 01:30 HRS. IN THE DEBRIS FROM THE FIRE, UPS PERSONNEL LOCATED FOUR 1-GALLON CANS OF DYKEM PAINT SOLVENT. THERE WAS NO REMAINING EVIDENCE OF THE OUTER PACKAGING FOR THE SOLVENT CANS. IT IS BELIEVED THAT ON OF THE CANS HAD LEAKED SOME OF THE SOLVENT, CAUSING THE RELEASE OF FLAMMABLE VAPORS. IMMEDIATELY BEFORE CATCHING FIRE, THE PACKAGE HAD DESCENDED A SLIDE, WHICH THE FIRE CHIEF SUSPECTED CAUSED A BUILD-UP OF STATIC ELECTRICITY, WHICH LIKELY IGNITED THE VAPORS WHEN DISCHARGED IN A SPARK.

column168: At approximately 1135 EST, R&L Carriers discovered that the drum has been punctured, releasing its entire contents (55 gallons) on to the trailer floor, and on to the asphalt below the trailer.  R&L then contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS).  ERTS then dispatched an environmental contractor (Morgan Environmental) to the site for clean-up activities.  Morgan personnel then overpacked the damaged drum, and applied absorbents to the released material in the trailer and on the asphalt.  The applied absorbents were then worked in thoroughly, swept up, and containerized.

Driver was dispatched to make fuel delivery to Halliburton/Noble Energy site on November 14, 2013.    At approximately 1930, driver drove to close to a ditch line.  The soil and gravel gave way to the weight of the truck.  As a result, the truck traveled into ditch line and rolled onto its side. Note:  The road was located on private property.    Driver was not injured.    Diesel fuel spilled on to ground.  Spill was limited to 25 gallons and was not released in any waterway.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 10, 2013 AT APPROXIMATELY 18:29 PERSONNEL IN THE CSXT AACA YARD DISCOVERED ACFX 200382, A RESIDUE TANK CAR OF ALCOHOLS N.O.S. LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER, LOCAL, STATE AND/OR FEDERAL AGENCIES AS APPLICABLE WERE NOTIFIED CHEMTREC REPORT # 2013-1110-00039. HEPACO, A CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THAT THE BOV OPERATING HANDLE WAS PINNED AND SEALED IN THE OPEN POSITION. CSX TRANSFLO SEAL NUMBER 3792553 WAS FOUND SEALED ON THE CAR. CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL REMOVED TRANSFLO SEAL CLOSED THE VALVE AND REPINNED AND SEALED THE CAR WITH SEAL ULINE 598851. THE LEAK WAS SECURED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT. THIS INCIDENT DID NOT REQUIRE A SPECIAL SWITCHING MOVE. THIS INCIDENT DOES NOT REQUIRE A 7.1 NARRI=551 5X(4+3+0)X(2+0)= 70

INTERSECTION IN SAN JUAN COUNTY, UTAH.  DURING TRANSIT, WATER SEPARATED FROM SOLID 11.E.(2) BY-PRODUCT MATERIAL THAT HAD SETTLED.  THE TRANSPORT OPERATOR HAD TO APPLY BRAKES SUDDENLY AND FIRMLY TO AVOID COLLIDING WITH A SUV THAT HAD ABRUPTLY ENTERED THE HIGHWAY IN FRONT OF THE TRANSPORT. THE WATER SLOSHED TO THE TOP OF THE BIN AND DOWN THE SIDE OF THE BIN ONTO U.S. 191. THERE WAS NO RUN-OFF FROM THE LANDING ON THE ROADWAY.  RADIATION STAFF TOOK RADIOLOGICAL SURVEYS OF THE AREA FINDING NO ALPHA MEASUREMENTS ABOVE BACKGROUND AND BETA-GAMMA MEASUREMENTS OF 0/70 MR/HR.  VERY LITTLE IF ANY MATERIAL WAS THERE TO SURVEY.  IT WAS CONCLUDED BY THE RESPONDER THAT NO ADDITIONAL CLEANUP WAS NEEDED OR NECESSARY.

column168: Primary  Lithium batteries were received  by Tradebe  Treatment and Recycling, LLC ("Tradebe")  in East Chicago, IN. , The battery  electrodes are  inspected  for contact covers.  If  a battery  is discovered  without  proper  contact  covers  Tradebe  applies cover  to the  electrodes. Once the  batteries are  inspected  and  the  electrodes have been   properly   covered,   the   batteries  are   manually   repackaged   into  55-gallon containers.  The containers are  labeled  and  staged  for shipment until  the  battery filled containers are offered for transportation to processing facility.    On November  21, 2013,  a load  of thirty-three (33)  containers and  one  pallet  of batteries of  various   types  ("Battery  Shipment")   was  loaded  onto  a  trailer   and transported  to  INMETCO battery  processing   facility  in  Ellwood   City,  PA,  by Thunderbird Trucking LLC (a division of Tradebe).  The Thunderbird driver arrived at INMETCO at approximately 11:00pm,  several  hours  before the INMETCO facility was  open  to  receive  inbound  shipments.The  Thunderbird driver   parked  the tractor  and  trailer  full of Battery Shipment  at an INMETCO onsite  staging  area  for inbound  and outbound shipments and stayed  in the cab of tractor with  the trailer still attached  to the tractor.    At approximately 2:45 am on the morning of November 22, 2013,   the driver awoke to rumbling sounds coming from the trailer.  He exited his tractor  to investigate the sounds  and observed  a red glow at the top of his trailer at the front (i.e., nose) of the trailer  and realized that  the Battery Shipment  had caught fire.   The driver  then  ran to the  other  vehicles  parked  at  the  INMETCO staging  area  and  advised  the  other drivers  of the fire. The other  drivers  quickly drove their vehicles off-site.  The Thunderbird driver  then  ran and alerted  the INMETCO guard shack of the incident. The guards  immediately contacted  the Ellwood City Fire Department (ECFD). ECFD was notified of the incident  at approximately 2:50am.  The ECFD arrived  on site at 2:57 am with eight (8) fire fighters  who assessed  the incident  as a "small fire" and proceeded  to extinguish  the fire believing three to four containers were involved.  At 3:21am the fire was contained  and the ECFD proceeded  to conduct "MOP UP STAGE" at the location. column43: HYDROCHLORIC ACID (HCL) 22 DEGREE BULK INHIBITED W/RD50
column168: There was a collision between an intra-plant steel slab train and our Cargo Tank Motor Vehicle at a crossing within the Arcelor Mittal Steel Plant.  The lead train car hit our cargo tank trailer on the frame rail on the curb side and pushed the trailer and tractor onto the driver side.  The rear portion of the trailer came to rest on top of a concrete Jersey Barrier, causing the edge of the front head to strike the steel rail, which punctured it at this location.  The rest of the cargo tank contained some scuffs and scars but contained the material well.  Hydrochloric acid leaked from this puncture site approximately the same way a 1 1/2" hose might lose product.    Great West Casualty Company was in the process of getting Inland Waters to perform the clean­ up, but we learned that EnviroServe, another hazmat clean-up service, already had some personnel and equipment on site.  They have a positive working relationship with Arcelor Mittal, so they took on the clean-up duties.  A lined vac truck was used to suck up the spilled acid from the puddle that had formed nearby.  It was able to remove product about as quickly as it was being released, so an estimated maximum of 500 gallons were on the ground at one time.  Bags  of soda ash were used to neutralize the trail of spilled acid.  Approximately 15 gallons of Hydrochloric Acid entered the intra-plant storm sewer system and reached the Strip Mill Water Treatment Plant, where it was treated.    The responding fire/hazmat crews determined it would be safest to empty all acid from the cargo tank (pumping into a vac truck) and remove all diesel fuel prior to up-righting the equipment. This was done, and the tractor and trailer were transported to the First Class Transport Terminal in Strasburg on 11119/2013. We learned soon after that the collected acid that had been spilled or removed from the cargo tank had been transported to a facility and properly disposed of. Photos are attached to further illustrate the damage to the cargo tank.  The collision occurred at or about 12:10 p.m. on 11115/2013 and the leak began at that time.  The driver and a railroad spotter were taken for medical evaluation and released later that afternoon. At 12:51 p.m. due to changes in wind direction, parts of the Arcelor Mittal Hot Mill and Cold Mill were evacuated.  Traffic into the plant through Harvard Road was stopped.  Only essential personnel were permitted in the spill area.  At 16:45 Arcelor Mittal Security received word that traffic and work could resume in the area.  The leak had been resolved and remaining product had been pumped off through holes drilled into the cargo tank within approximately 4• hours. Clean-up ended at 20:05 hours and Richard's  Towing removed the First Class Transport truck at20:50.
column169: Arcelor Mittal has been communicating changes to their site in the vicinity of the plant acid tank which will allow Cargo Tank Motor Vehicles to make delivery without crossing the railroad tracks twice.  This involves moving a fire hydrant and water line, road widening, additional paving, and installation of a guardrail between the new truck turn around area and the plant rail system.  I understand this was a recommendation of the U.S. Coast Guard.  Work was underway soon after the event, possibly the next week day, and I understand the guardrail and fire hydrant re-installation are the final remaining projects which are expected to be completed soon.  This should make the plant are much safer for commercial drivers and the intra-plant railroad personnel and prevent any future recurrence oftrain-acid tanker collision.    It is our opinion that if the cargo tank had rolled over onto the rail and the rear of the trailer had not been elevated on the Jersey Barrier, the tank would not have ruptured.  If the tank had come down on the dirt or a flat paved surface, we don't  think it would have ruptured.  We are very impressed with the strength of the Tankcon unit given the amount of punishment it received. This was basically a freak accident where the cargo tank rolled in such a way that resulted in the edge of the front head coming down directly on a rail, which punctured it.

column168: Leaking tank on vesselMsk Danang  BLKU2510962, Un 1760, Class 8, Corrosive Liquid Nos (Sodium Hydroxide,Sodium Sulfide)  POHA Report 131-2283 Officer Miller  POHA isolated 100ft before and aft of area, Hatch 3, Bay 26  POHA Captain: Tom Neskoa; 361-798-6462,POHAtightenedthe safety valve    While working the vessel a AOM noticed a sulfide like odor and said saw some liquid on the hatch cover. He then advised marine department. The erh ployees were removed from the vessel, POHA police department was notified and requested to respond. FSO/HSE manager was notified. HSE retrieved  paperwork  and tried to call the 24 hour emergency number  but the number  was not a complete number. She then proceeded to contact Maersk-line Kimberly Pate ad requested a material safety data sheet.  POHA responded, suited up, and went on the vessel. They tested the product  and stated there was a very slow drip and apprx. one cup of liquid under the valve on the hath cover. They tapped the valve to tighten it.   A discussion was held to leave the tank on the  vessel until, M&M came on sight to determine could the tank be lifted off the vessel without any further leak, no threat  to  persons, or environment i.e. water or property. It was determined it was safe to discharge the tank onto a chassis. The tank did not appear to be leaking.   The blue product on the hatch cover was dried product  approximately 2-3 gallons approximately 2'x12'x16; area.   POHA maintained a 100-l5Oft before and aft of the hatch. The gangs were allowed to go back to work but not the area of the tank.   HSE Manager made notifications as applicable.  HSE advised the line the tank had actually leaked but the drip was very slow and rarely seen. HSE advised that the emergency response vendor must be called in. The line contacted M&M Protection. M&M came dn scene. They went on aboard and cleaned up the one cup of free liquid, neutralized  the residual (dried) appx 2-3 gallons on the hatch cover, and scraped up materials. M&M Protection  took air monitoring readings when they arrived to the tank area. The area was safe. All materials were placed in drums and bags for disposal.   The tank was put on chassis and discharged from the vessel at approximately 1:57 p.m. Before moving the tank M&M inspected the valve. It was decided we wanted to check the cap see if there was any residual inside the cap. The valve did not appear to be seated properly. barely off (see photo). The tank was taken to C1 isolation area, cap removed, appx.l-2 quarts was in the cap. The valve handle was realigned and it seated properly. M&M put a seal on the valve.      Tank Specifications (refer to photo):  Weight:36000kgs, 793581bs  ACEB-CB119, 04-2008  Hydrualic 25-04-2003  Inspection 08-05  5 yr 07-08, 06/11  Manufacturer 04-2003, serial G-203-08  New seal by M&M: SSC3333573    I believe this event was handled very well. Coordination, Clean up was good. Employees were removed and safe work area. was determined. Vessel operations  w

(DETAILED REPORT OF TIMES AND EVENTS ON FILE, WITH PICTURES ON RECORD OF SCENE AND AS CLEANUP TOOK PLACE)    ACCIDENT WITH DAVID SHERRILL TOOK PLACE AT APPROX. 4:30 AM, NOV 07, 2013 WHILE LOADED WITH(UN 1267 PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL,3,II) COMING DOWN DANIELS CANYON WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 40 AT MILE POST 25.   WHILE MAKING A SWEEPING LEFT HAND TURN, NOTICED THE SECOND TRAILER WAS OFF OF HARD ROAD SURFACE AND AS DRIVER REPORTED HE JERKED IT BACK ONTO THE ROAD AND AS HE DID THE SECOND TRAILER OVERTURNED, ROLLING OVER ONCE AND LANDING ON ITS RIGHT SIDE. DRIVER STOPPED AND RAN BACK. HE NOTICED IT WAS LEAKING OIL FROM RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF TRAILER AND CALLED 911 AND THE COMPANY (SUMMIT OIL). HE TALKED TO DENNIS CHRISTENSEN. HE WAS ASKED IF THERE WERE ANY INJURIES OR OTHER SECONDARY ACCIDENTS WHICH THERE WAS NONE. EMERGENCY CREWS ARRIVED FROM WASATCH FIRE DEPARTMENT AND UTAH HIGHWAY PATROL, FOLLOWED BY UTAH AIR AND HEALTH DEPT. THEY CONTAINED THE SPILL FROM ENTERING ANY WATERWAY.  STEVE JOHNSON WITH SUMMIT OIL DISPATCHED COMPANY'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ALONG WITH A PUMP TRUCK TO RECOVER AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.  BULLOCKS TOWING WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE FOR EQUIPMENT RECOVERY ALONG WITH ENVIROCARE RETAINED AS OUR CLEANUP COMPANY. THEY BOTH ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 6:30 AM AND TOOK OVER THE CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP.  STEVE JOHNSON NOTIFIED NATIONAL RESPONSE AND WAS ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER #1065118.  STATE OF UTAH (DEQ), WAS NOTIFIED ALSO OF THE ACCIDENT AND WAS REPORTED TO THEM THE NATIONAL RESPONSE REPORT NUMBER.  ROAD WAY WAS NEVER CLOSED AND MEDIA WAS NEVER AT SCENE. NO SPILLED OIL MADE IT TO ANY WATERWAY.  UTAH DOT INVESTIGATOR ARRIVED AT SCENE AND INSPECTED EACH PIECE OF EQUIPMENT AND NO VIOLATIONS WERE ISSUED TO THE COMPANY WITH EXCEPTIONS OF ITEMS CAUSED BY THE CRASH TO THE SECOND TRAILER. THE TRACTOR AND FIRST TRAILER WAS RELEASED TO SALT LAKE TO UNLOAD. SUMMIT OIL HAD A RELIEF DRIVER ON SCENE TO DRIVER THAT TRACTOR AND CRASHED PULL TRAILER WAS TOWED TO SUMMIT OIL TRUCK YARD BY BULLOCKS TOWING. DRIVER WAS CITED IMPROPER LANE CHANGE, AND WAS RELEASED AT SCENE TO GO WITH A COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE FOR A POST-ACCIDENT DRUG AND ALCOHOL TEST, WHICH WAS DONE. THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER WANTED TO KNOW THE RESULTS OF THE DRUG TEST WHICH CAME BACK POSITIVE. A COPY OF THE DRUG TEST WAS SENT TO THEM AS REQUESTED. THE ATTENDING DOCTOR AT THE DRUG AND ALCOHOL TESTING FACILITY NOTIFIED MR SHERRILL OF THE POSITIVE RESULTS TO WHICH HE WAS REPORTED AS TO HAVE NO EXPLANATION.  SUMMIT OIL INVESTIGATED THE SCENE AND HAS COME TO THE CONCLUSION THAT THERE WAS NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE AND THAT THE ACCIDENT WILL BE NOTED AS DRIVER ERROR.  A SUMMIT OIL REVIEW BOARD REVIEWED THIS INCIDENT ON MONDAY 11/11/13 AND HAS COME TO THE CONCLUSION OF DRIVER ERROR AND HAS DETERMINED TO TERMINATE MR. SHERRILL
column169: ALSO BOARD RECOMMENDED AND PLANNED AN EXTENSIVE SAFETY MEETING WHICH WAS HELD 11/12/13 AT 2:PM      ITEMS DISCUSSED WERE LABELED AS (DISTRACTION'S AT WHAT COST)     ITEMS DISCUSSED WERE (THIS ACCIDENT, CAUSES, PRECAUTIONS, DISTRACTIONS, JOURNEY PLANS AND UPDATES, STRESS, FATIGUE, ROAD CONDITIONS, REST PERIODS, SAFETY STOPS, LIGHTS ON FOR SAFETY, ADDITIONAL HAZARDS, HAZMAT, WINTER DRIVING AND NEW FR CLOTHING HAS ARRIVED)    ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CONTINUES AND IS EXPECTED TO BE COMPLETED ON FRIDAY 11/15/13 PENDING SOIL SAMPLE RESULTS. CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IS BEING STORED IN ROLL OFF BINS AT ENVIROCARE FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL PERMITS.     UNIT #213 (PULL TRAILER) WAS CLASSIFIED AS A TOTAL AND WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW PULL TRAILER WHICH ARRIVES IN SLC ON 11/15/13.    COMPLETE ACCIDENT FILE LOCATED AT SUMMIT OIL OFFICE.    1180 NORTH ALFRED AVE, KAYSVILLE, UTAH 84037    CONTACT PERSON IS STEVE JOHNSON (801-721-7675)    PREPARED BY     STEVE JOHNSON    SUMMIT OIL MANAGER  11/14/2013

column168: Tank transport hauling anhydrous ammonia was eastbound on Hwy 11.  As it approached Hwy E, a tow truck travelling north on E was unable to stop at the intersection, and the transport struck the driver's side of the tow truck, just behind the driver's door.  Both vehicles ended up in the ditch, with the transport on it's side.  Liquid ammonia leaked from the pressure-relief valve on top of the tank, and it pooled up on the ground until it eventually vaporized.  It leaked for about 8 hours, until the product was transferred to another transport and the transport was uprighted.  An environmental clean-up company came to the site after the vehicles were removed and remediated the soil that was contaminated with ammonia and also diesel fuel from the vehicle saddle tanks.
column169: We will continue to train our drivers in defensive driving, but all indication is that our driver could not have avoided the collision.  The tank and other appurtances survived the collision, and the pressure-relief valve is not designed to be in contact with liquid product.

column168: Dispatch number 1542, shipped under United States Post Office tracking number   EC-204-801-696-US/ 1pc weighing 30.3kgs, consisted of a parcel containing 24 Fibreboard Boxes of paint canisters (UN1263 / total net qty. 24 x 950ml).  The mail shipment originated in New York (JFKIA) and was accepted by Emirates from the United States Post Office as a mail consignment, under document number AV-7: USB3EJF01909. The parcel was then transported on flight EK202 on November 11th, 2014 from JFK International Airport to Dubai International Airport. The shipment was packaged in a way that prevented Emirates’ handling staff from verifying its contents without opening the parcel. Contents were discovered during a routine x-ray screening of transit mail by the Dubai Police. After Dubai Police opened the package, it was discovered that the internal boxes contained the paint canisters in original packaging. Hazmat documentation was not provided to Emirates by the  shipper at the time of tender. After classifying shipment as suspect D.G., Emirates contacted the shipper for confirmation of the contents. At which point the shipper stated that an MSDS would be provided.  However, till date shipper has not been able to provide Emirates with an MSDS and has been incooperative. Emirates was able to obtain an MSDS from the manufacturer's website confirming the clasification of the hazardous material.  The shipment is currently being held in Dubai, until shipper appoints an agent to perform proper markings, labeling, and documentation. Only after all IATA/ICAO and FAA requirements have been met, will the shipment be moved to its final destination in Moscow, or returned back to the shipper.

column168: THE DRIVER SAW SMOKE COMING FROM THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE POWER UNIT AND STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE. WHEN THE DRIVER EXITED THE CAB THERE WAS SMOKE COMING FROM THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRACTOR NEAR THE CENTER AROUND THE REAR OF THE HOOD AND PASSENGER SIDE DOOR. VERY QUICKLY THE ENTIRE POWER UNIT WAS ENGULFED IN FLAMES. THE DRIVER CALLED 911. APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES LATER THE FIRE SPREAD TO THE TRACTOR DRIVE TIRES ON THE PASSENGER SIDE WHICH CAUSED EXTREME HEAT ON THE BOTTOM CYLINDERS (TUBES) OF THE TRAILER. IT IS PRESUMED THAT THE EXTREME HEAT CAUSED A SEAL IN THE BULL PLUG OF THE CYLINDER TO MELT AND COMPRESSED GAS (HYDROGEN) BEGAN TO FLOW AND IGNITED. THE FIRE CONTINUED TO BURN SLOWLY UNTIL CUSTOMER PERSONNEL LOWERED THE PRESSURE IN THE CYLINDER WHICH STOPPED THE FLOW OF GAS AND THE FIRE SELF EXTINGUISHED.    THE TRAILER IS COMMONLY REFERRED TO AS A TUBE TRAILER. IT CONSISTS OF 10 3AAX CYLINDERS. THE CYLINDER HAS WHAT IS KNOWN AS A BULL PLUG IN THE END AND THEN AN INTERNAL BURST DISK ASSEMBLY IS SCREWED INTO THE BULL PLUG. THE BURST DISK DOES NOT APPEAR TO HAVE FAILED. AT THIS TIME IT IS PRESUMED THAT THE SEAL BETWEEN THE BULL PLUG AND THE CYLINDER END MELTED AND CAUSED THE LEAK.    THE DRIVER STOPPED AT APPROXIMATELY 14:50 AND HIGHWAY 60 WAS CLOSED AT THAT TIME. THE UNITS WERE RELEASED TO A TOWING COMPANY APPROXIMATELY 7 HOURS LATER.    THE PRIMARY CAUSE OF THE TRACTOR FIRE IS UNDER INVESTIGATION AND WELL AS THE INSPECTION OF THE CYLINDERS TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.

column168: The cause of the spill was determined to be from faulty maintenance.  On October 28, 2013, Fred received a work order for the installation of a cam lock fitting on the diesel tank at Mountain View.  The threads for the riser where the drivers fill the tank were stripped and Fred decided to look for another riser to use.  Fred used the riser for the interstitial space; he assumed that the gage was to measure inventory in the tank.  Fred did not conduct any other tests or asked for any advice to ascertain that the riser he selected was the correct one.  When Aloha’s driver showed up for the next delivery he connected to the new port, which was actually the interstitial space, and overfilled the tank.
column169: Since the spill, maintenance moved the tank’s fill port back to the proper port.

AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 AM ON NOVEMBER 14TH, 2013, MORNING GLORY DAIRY FACILITY PERSONNEL OBSERVED THE CAM LOCK SECURING THE HOSE TO THE FACILITY'S VITEX AAC 60 TANK HAD VIBRATED LOOSE AND THE HOSE HAD DETACHED FROM THE TANK RELEASING AN ESTIMATED 43-50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE OF THE YARD. FREE PRODUCT FURTHER MIGRATED INTO A STORM DRAIN. AN EMERGENCY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE WAS IMMEDIATELY RETAINED TO MANAGE THE CLEAN UP. PH TESTS WERE TAKEN IN THE STORM DRAIN OUTFALL AT SEVERAL POINTS. SAMPLES RETURNED AT NEUTRAL LEVELS. IT WAS DETERMINED NO FREE PRODUCT MIGRATED FROM THE OUT FALLS. USING A CAUSTIC CLEANER, MATERIAL RELEASED INTO THE OUTFALLS WAS NEUTRALIZED BY THE EMERGENCY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE.
column169: QUEST LINER WAS THE CARRIER FOR THIS SHIPMENT, HOWEVER, MORNING GLORY FARMS (CONSIGNEE) WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE UNLOADING OF THE PRODUCT. OUR RECOMMENDATION WOULD BE FOR THE CONSIGNEE TO IMPLEMENT THE USE OF REMOVABLE CLAMPS OR STRAPS THAT SURROUND THE CAM LOCK CONNECTIONS THAT WOULD HELP PREVENT THEM FROM COMING LOOSE DUE TO VIBRATION.

column168: WHILE TRAVELLING SOUTHBOUND ON I-65 IN KENTUCKY OUR DRIVER NOTICED WHAT APPEARED TO BE ANTIFREEZE LEAKING FROM THE SEMI TRAILER. HE PULLED IN THE REST AREA AND ATTEMPTED TO PARK IN AN ISOLATED AREA. AT 1330, DRIVER CALLED 911 AND THE HOME OFFICE AND WAITED BY THE TRAILER FOR EMERGENCY CREWS TO ARRIVE. HAZMAT TEAMS CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH EARTHEN DAMS AND CONTAINMENT POOLS. THE HAZMAT TEAMS DETERMINED THE TRAILER AND SURROUNDING AREAS WERE NOT AN IDLH ATMOSPHERE, LELS WERE BELOW LEVELS OF CONCERN AND RELEASED THE SITE TO THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR. AT 18:23, THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR BEGAN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THE WASTE MATERIAL TO IDENTIFY THE LEAKING DRUM AND REMEDIATE THE SPILLED WASTE WITHIN THE TRAILER. ACCORDING TO TECHNICIANS AT THE SCENE, ONE POLY DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A SMALL CRACK IN THE SIDEWALL NEAR THE BASE OF THE DRUM. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 6 GALLONS LEFT IN THE DRUM WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED.THE DRUM AND ALL SORBENT MATERIALS GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP  WERE OVERPACKED AND SHIPPED FOR DISPOSAL TO THE DESIGNATED FACILITY. THE INCIDENT SCENE WAS CLEARED AT APPROXIMATELY 21:30.
column169: NO COMMENTS WERE PROVIDED.

column168: Driver was traveling at highway speed and went off the right side of roadway. Correcting the unit back onto the highway the pup trailer lost control and layed over on it's side. The impact split seams out of the head and rear bulkheads allowing product to escape. Trailer drug over 700' and tore skin more allowing entire contents to spill on both sides of the 2 lane roadway.   Driver stopped put out warning devices and guarded the roadway till emergency services could arrive and assist. Hanser's Wrecker service out of Billings brought in fly ash and loaders to soak up as much residue off the highway as possible and secured the area till Montana Environmental and LMH environmental (contracted with insurance) determined the spill area and disposal method of contaminated soil. Remediation has been completed and we are waiting for Montana DEQ to release the claim.
column169: All drivers reviewed the accident and viewed the PHMSA FMCSA video on tank rollover. Distracted driving was reviewed as well even though no evidence of typical distractions were discovered. Possible lane departure warning devices could help in the prevention of future ROR accidents in the industry.

column168: PRAXAIR VEHICLE (VEHICLE #1) WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON 1-75 AT MILE MARKER 97 NEAR SIDNEY, OH IN THE RIGHT LANE OF THE HIGHWAY. VEHICLE #1, (PRAXAIR VEHICLE) HAD JUST BEEN PASSED BY ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER (VEHICLE #2) WHEN A THIRD TRACTOR TRAILER (VEHICLE #3) PULLED ONTO THE ROADWAY FROM THE SHOULDER AND CROSSED INTO THE RIGHT TRAVEL LANE. VEHICLE #1 SWERVED TO THE LEFT BUT WAS UNABLE TO AVOID CONTACT WITH THE REAR OF THE SLOW MOVING VEHICLE #3. THE RESULTING COLLISION CAUSED VEHICLE #1 TO OVERTURN. AFTER OVERTURNING, AND WHILE EMT'S WERE TREATING THE DRIVER, DIESEL FUEL CAUGHT FIRE AND THE FIRE CONSUMED THE CAB OF VEHICLE 1.    AFTER OVERTURNING, THE VACUUM INSULATED CRYOGENIC TRAILER OF VEHICLE #1 LOST VACUUM AND THE RATE OF LIQUID NITROGEN EVAPORATION INCREASED, RAISING THE PRESSURE AND CAUSING THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVES TO FUNCTION. BECAUSE THE TRAILER OF VEHICLE #1 WAS OVERTURNED, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE INLET PIPING WAS SUBMERGED UNDER LIQUID NITROGEN CAUSING LIQUID NITROGEN AND CRYOGENIC NITROGEN VAPOR TO BE EXPELLED.
column169: NO RECOMMENDATIONS ARE CURRENTLY PROPOSED WITH RESPECT TO THE NON-SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK AS THE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS THE RESULT OF PROPER FUNCTIONING OF PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICES THAT BECAME SUBMERGED UNDER LIQUID NITROGEN FOLLOWING COLLISION AND OVERTURNING OF VEHICLE #1.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER AND A HOSE CLAMP FAILED ON A AERATOR LINE AND IT BLEW OFF THE BOTTOM OF THE HOPPER CONE, ALLOWING 800 POUNDS OF PRODUCT TO FLOW OUT OF THE TRAILER ON TO THE GROUND BEFORE THE PRESSURE COULD BE RELIEVED OFF OF THE TRAILER. THIS HAPPENED DURING A RAIN EVENT SO THEY ISOLATED THE PRODUCT AND THE RUNOFF OF STORM WATER. A ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP CREW WAS BROUGHT IN TO CLEAN UP AND RECYCLE/DISPOSE THE LEAD AS WELL RECYCLE/DISPOSE THE LEAD AS WELL AS DESPOSE OF THE STORM WATER.
column169: THIS TRAILER WAS LEASED TO GEORGIA OXIDE AND THE MAINTENANCE OF IT WAS SHARED BY THE SHIPPER AND CARRIER AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE AERATOR LINE HOSE CLAMPS WERE NOT GETTING INSPECTED AND MAINTAINED AS NEEDED BY GEORGIA OXIDE. TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN WE BULKMATIC HAVE TAKEN ALL PREVENTABLE MAINTENANCE RESPONSIBLY FOR THE LEASED TRAILERS AND PUT THEM ON A PM SCHEDULE TO INSURE ALL COMPONENTS OF THE TRAILERS ARE BEING INSPECTED AND MAINTAINED.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING DOWN GRAVEL ROAD PULLING DOUBLE TANKS. THE TANKS BEGAN TO KICK OUT AWAY FROM THE VEHICLE AND THE DRIVER SLOWED BY HITTING THE VEHICLE BRAKES. WHEN SLOWING THE VEHICLE IT CAUSED THE TANKS TO FURTHER KICK OUT AND ROLL, DISCONNECTING FROM THE VEHICLE. ONLY ONE TANK WAS DAMAGED WITH THE VALVE BEING RIPPED AWAY IN THE ROLL OVER CAUSING THE RELEASE OF NH3. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT OUT OF SYRACUSE RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. THEY SPRAYED WATER ON THE VAPOR CLOUD TO KEEP IT FROM SPREADING UNTIL THE TANK WAS DONE RELEASING. THE VAPOR CLOUD WAS ESTIMATED TO BE 20 FEET IN DIAMETER.

column168: ON THE NOVEMBER 21, 2013 AT 0600. WE HAD A TRUCK DRIVER GUSTAVO GAMEZ. GUSTAVO GAMEZ WAS DRIVING A SEMI TRUCK. GUSTAVO GAMES WAS TRAVELLING ON I-10 WB TOWARDS TUCSON, AZ. GUSTAVO GAMEZ HIT A CAR (CHEVY CRUZ) BEING TOWED BY A NISSAN PATHFINDER, WHICH WAS TOWED BY A TOYOTA MINIVAN (ALL TOWED BY THE BUMPERS). THESE VEHICLES WERE TOWED ILLEGALLY WITHOUT TOW LIGHTS AND AT A SLOW SPEED. ACCORDING TO THE DPS AGENTS THESE VEHICLES WERE DRIVING 35MPH IN A 75 MPH ZONE, OUR DRIVER WAS GOING 65 MPH. IT WAS STILL DARK OUTSIDE. GUSTAVO GAMES STATED HE HAD NO TIME TO REACT WITHOUT HITTING THE VEHICLE.   GUTSAVO GAMEZ HIT THE REAR VEHICLE (CHEVY CRUZ). CAUSING THE OTHER VEHICLES TO LOSE CONTROL. GUSTAVO GAMEZ TRUCK ROLLED ON ITS SIDE AND SPILT PRODUCT (COPPER CONCENTRATE). ABOUT 20,000 LBS. OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED OUT OF THE TRAILERS. I WAS ON SCENE AT 0700. UPON MY ARRIVAL I CALLED IN OUR HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM CT ENVIRONMENTAL. CT ENVIRONMENTAL DONE OUR CLEAN UP AND VEHICLES WERE TOWED AWAY. THE I-10 WAS CLOSED DOWN FOR ABOUT 4 HOURS.
column169: WE HAVE NOTIFIED ALL OUR DRIVERS OF THE VEHICLES BEING TOWED WITHOUT LIGHTS AND BEING TOWED AT A VERY SLOW SPEED. THEY SHOULD BE AWARE OF WHAT IS IN FRONT OF THEM.

column168: DRIVER EXCEEDED THE ASSIGNED SPEED LIMIT IN A POSTED 30 MPH TURN RESULTING IN FULL TANKER LOAD ROLLOVER. LOAD CONSISTED OF TWO COMPARTMENTS OF DIESEL FUEL AND ONE COMPARTMENT OF GASOLINE. DURING ROLLOVER THE FIRST COMPARTMENT CONTAINING DIESEL FUEL WAS COMPROMISED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF 1,066 GAL OF DIESEL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO A 1000 FOOT AREA OF A ROAD SIDE DITCH. MITIGATION, CLEAN UP, REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATES WERE ACCOMPLISHED BY OMI ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS OF SHREVERPORT LA.
column169: A TOP TO BOTTOM REVIEW OF OUR TRAINING PROCEDURES OUR COMPANY COMPLETED. RETRAINED ALL OF OUR DRIVER THRU SAFETY BRIEFINGS  RECERTIFICATION FINALS AND NO NOTICE RIDE ALONGS WITH SAFETY INBPOTORS.  DRIVER INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT WAS RELEASED. TRAILER HAD WITHIN 10 DAYS OF ACCIDENT SEEN INSPECTED, CHANGED BREAKS SPRITQS AND HUBS. TRUCK HAD JUST BEEN PM'D. ROAD CONDITIONS WERE GOOD ROAD WAY SIGNAGE WAS VERY GOOD. THIS ACCIDENT WAS ATTRIBUTED TO DRIVER ERROR.

column168: THE DRIVER, CARELTON MIGUESS, TRUCK #343, TRAILER #468, WAS LOADING HIS TRAILER AT THE EASTHAM 1-1 LEASE 3 116276 NEAR WELDON, HOUSTON COUNTY, TX.  HE THEN REENTERED HIS TRUCK TO COMPLETE PAPERWORK AND DOZED OFF.  WHEN HE EXITED HIS TRUCK, HE DISCOVERED THAT HIS TRAILER OVERFLOWED RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 33 BBLS OF CRUDE PRODUCT TO SOIL AT THE LEASE WITH NO PRODUCT LEAVING THE SITE.  THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES.  THE RELEASE OCCURED AT APPROXIMATELY 04:35 ON NOVEMBER 16. 2013, FROM THE OVERFLOW VENT ON HIS TRAILER CAUSED BY OPERATOR ERROR.  UPON DISCOVERY, THE DRIVER NOTIFIED DISPATCH AND THE FIELD SAFETY REPRESENTATIVE OF THE RELEASE WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE COMPANY ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT AND CALLED FOR A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND.  AN EARTHEN DIKE WAS PLACED AROUND THE RELEASE BY THE DRIVER TO PREVENT SPREAD OF THE OIL.  THE CLEANUP CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AND PICKED UP THE FREE PRODUCT IN A VACUUM TRUCK AND EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOIL.  SOIL SAMPLES WERE ALSO COLLECTED TO INDICATE COMPLETE REMOVAL TO BACKGROUND LEVELS.
column169: ALL CURRENT DRIVERS WERE INFORMED OF THE RELEASE AND ITS ROOT CAUSE.  INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO PREVENT FUTURE RELEASES OF THIS NATURED FROM OCCURING BY BEING MORE DILIGENT DURING THE LOADING PROCESS BY BEING BY THE LOADING CONTROLS AT ALL TIME WHILE TRANSFERRING PRODUCT WERE GIVEN TO THEM ALSO.  THESE INSTRUCTIONS ARE INCORPORATED INTO OUR DRIVER TRAINING PROGRAM FOR ALL NEW HIRES AS WELL.

column168: ON WEDNESDAY NOVEMEBER 27, 2013 A CONSOLIDATED OIL WELL SERVICES DRIVER LEFT THE BARTIESVILLE OKLAHOMA TERMINAL AT 0600 TO GO TO A JOB SITE NEAR EL DORADO KANSAS.  HE MADE IT NORTH OF SEDAN KS ON HWY K99 AROUND 0700 WERE HE LEFT THE ROADWAY AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER HE WAS OPERATING ROLLED. WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED AND THE TANK WAS COMPROMISED WHICH HAS BEEN FILLED WITH 4500 GALLONS OF 15% ACID. THERE WAS A LOSS OF 3700 GALLONS OF ACID THAT WAS LOST INTO A COW PASTURE AND INTO A RUN OFF WHICH LEADS TO A POND. THE LAND OWNER WAS NOTIFIED THAT MORNING OF THE ACCIDENT AND THAT CLEAN-UP WAS BEING TAKEN PLACE. KDHE WAS NOTIFED FILE NUMBER(2711130920HH) AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFED FILE NUMBER (1067023) THE CHAUTAUQUA COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS NOTIFED AS WELL AS HAZ-MAT RESPONSE OUT OF OLATHE KS. THE RELEASE OF THE ACID OCCURED FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES. A TRACK HOE WAS BROUGHT IN TO BUILD A BERM SO TO STOP AND SPREAD TO THE POND. THE RELEASE OF THE ACID WAS CAUSED DUE TO THE ROLL OVER WHICH COMPROMISED THE LIDS AND CAUSED AN HALF INCH BY THREE INCH CRACK IN THE TANK.  BY 1530 HRS HAZ-MAT REPONSE HAD THE CONTAMINATED SOIL CONTAINED ON TARPS AND COVERED BY MORE TARPS.
column169: COSOLIDATED OIL WELL SERVICES HAS MADE NEW POLICIES ON DRIVING NARROW TWO LANE HIGHWAYS. DRIVER ARE NOT TO TAKE NARROW TWO LANE HIGHWAYS UNLESS THAT IS THE ONLY ROUTE POSSIBLE. WHEN DRIVING NARROW TWO LANE HIGHWAYS THE MAX SPEED IS NOW 50 MPH.  BEFORE ANY TRUCK LEAVES THE TERMINALS THERE WILL BE A SAFETY MEETING HELD AND THE ROUTE WILL BE GONE OVER.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED ON NOVEMBER 12, 2013 AT APPROXIMATELY 1150.    DRIVER ENTERED THE CLOVER LEAF OF THE EXIT TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 30 MPH. IN THE TURN, HIS LOAD SHIFTED CAUSING HIM TO LOSE CONTROL AND THE TRACTOR/TRAILER TO ROLL OVER. DURING THE ROLL , THE VENT RELEASE SWITCH OPENED THE VENTS ALLOWING THE DIESEL TO FLOW FREELY FROM THEIR COMPARTMENTS. IN APPROXIMATELY 10 TO 15 MINUTES THE ENTIRE 7500 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS RELEASED. ANOTHER COMPANY DRIVER ARRIVED ON THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE ROLL OVER AND ASSISTED OUR DRIVER OUT THE TRACTOR. 911 WAS CALLED AND THEN OUR LOCAL DISPATCHERS WERE INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT. DRIVER OF THE ROLLED VEHICLE WAS EXAMINED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL. HE WAS RELEASED AND BACK TO OUR OFFICE BY 1600. COUNTY PERSONNEL WERE THE FIRST TO ARRIVE AND THEY BLOCKED THE FUEL FROM ENTER THE WATERWAY. OUR OSRO, UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, WAS NOTIFIED WITHIN A FEW MINUTES OF THE INCIDENT AND ARRIVED ON THE SCENE IN LESS THAN 60 MINUTES. LOCAL FACILITY PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON SCENE WITHIN 20 MINUTES OF THE INCIDENT. OUR COMPANY OWNER AND I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1400. BY THE TIME THAT I ARRIVED, OUR OSRO, COUNTY PERSONNEL, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE DEPARTMENT, ALABAMA STATE POLICE AND A TOWING SERVICE WAS ON THE SCENE.    WE CONTACTED THE SERVICES OF PPM CONSULTANTS, AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANT, TO OVERSEE THE CLEAN UP OF THE AFFECTED SITE. PPM DID SOIL SAMPLING TO ENSURE THAT THE REMEDIATION WAS PROPERLY HANDLED.
column169: OUR DRIVER WAS REQUIRED TO VIEW SEVERAL ON LINE SAFETY CLASSES AND PASS THE ASSOCIATED TEST/QUIZ. AFTER THESE COURSES WERE FINISHED, HE WAS REQUIRED TO ATTEND AND PASS A 40 HOUR DOT DRIVING COURSE. ONCE THIS WAS COMPLETED, THIS DRIVER WAS REQUIRED TO DRIVE SEVERAL DAYS WITH THREE OF OUR MORE EXPERIENCED DRIVERS. ALL OF THIS DRIVER'S RE-TRAINING WAS SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETED AND HE WAS RETURNED TO WORK.  THE PARTICULAR TRAILER THAT WAS INVOLVED IN THIS ACCIDENT HAD A VENT RELEASE SWITCH THAT OPENED ALL COMPARTMENT VENTS WHEN THE DOOR TO THE BELLY VALVE COMPARTMENT WAS OPENED. DURING THE ROLL OVER, THIS COMPARTMENT DOOR OPENED THUS OPENING ALL OF THE VENTS AND ALLOWED THE DIESEL TO FLOW FREELY BEFORE ANYONE WAS ABLE TO DO ANYTHING TO MITIGATE THE SITUATION.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT INTO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AND THE OVERFILL ALARM ON THE TANK DID NOT ACTIVATE COMBINED WITH FAILURE OF HE HOSE END COUPLING TO SEAL PROPERLY. THE SPILLED PRODUCT PROCEEDED ALONG THE EDGE OF THE HIGHWAY PAVEMENT AND ENTERED A STORMWATER DRAIN. THE CARGO TANK DID NOT FAIL. THE DRIVER SCATTERED SOME ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE SPILLED FUEL AND PROCEEDED TO ANOTHER LOCATION TO FINISH UNLOADING THE PRODUCT. WE HIRED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO SCRUB THE PAVEMENT AND FLUSH THE STORMWATER DRAIN TO ENSURE THAT WE HAD RECOVERED THE SPILLED PRODUCT AND PREVENT FURTHER DOWNSTREAM CONTAMINATION.
column169: 1)WE REPAIRED THE OVERFILL ALARM SYSTEM AND THIS LOCATION.    2)WE IMPLEMENTED NEW UNLOADING PROCEDURES TO INSURE THAT THERE IS ADEQUATE SPACE IN THE TANK FOR THE PRODUCT.    3)WE HELD DRIVER TRAINING SESSIONS IN DECEMBER OF 2013 TO REVIEW PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES AND THE REQUIRMENT FOR BEING IN ATTENDANCE DURING ALL UNLOADING ACTIVITIES.

column168: When TSA opened the passengers checked bag for inspection, an odor was noted.  Upon further inspection, the can of aerosol lubricant was discovered in the passengers bag.  The can was contained inside a platic bag.  The aerosol can did not have a protective cap and it appeared that something pushed against the top causing the lubricant to discharge. There appeared to be no punctures or signs of failure on the can. TSA removed the item from the passengers bag and turned it over to a Southwest Airlines employee.
